column11: At 9am, the SS Riverdale brought up in the Bay in 8 fathoms half mile NE of Pier end owing to some grievance. Some of her crew are landed 5pm and a fresh lot taken off and shipped. She is also bunkering.

column11: At 1.46 pm, while the Riverdale was getting under way, the cook jumped overboard. The 2nd Officer, named Osborne, jumped overboard to save the cook. They were both brought ashore in ship's small boat but although artificial respiration was given life was extinct in both cases.

column11: Sunday 2nd. Rumours of war. RNR called out and proceeding to Portsmouth. Strict watch kept at the harbour. Telephone message at 8pm, supposed engagement 70 east of Aberdeen. Hospital ship proceeding to this port.

column10: Monday 3rd. Strong southerly wind and squally. Sea rough.
column11: Monday 3rd. Several reserve trawlers were manned today and proceed to their respective stations for mine sweeping purposes. Fishing completely paralized and harbour Confeated.

column10: Tuesday 4th. First part of day showery, middle and latter parts fine.

Wednesday 5th. War declared against Germany. Great excitement. Territorials called up. 3 prizes in Port. Trawler Elsie Coazle, Handle, Warden & St Broazeel
Thursday 6th. Six of HM RNR Mine Sweepers put in here last night on their way to Cromarty, still fitting out for war at this point.

column10: Friday 7th. Fine weather with occasional showers.
column11: Friday 7th. Still manning the Mine Sweepers with RNR men. Several destroyers passed North about 10 miles off. Another capture, the Ger Aux Craft Willi.
column12: Inconsistency in Ships numbers. Sheet started at 1548, should have been 1558

column10: Wednesday 30th. Strong northerly wind and showery. Sea moderate.
Thursday 1st October. Fresh northerly wind and moderate sea. Sky cloudy.
Friday 2nd. First and middle part fine, latter fresh, westerly wind & showery.
Saturday 3rd. Strong northerly wind and squally. Sea moderate.
Sunday 4th. Fine weather with smooth sea. Brisk northerly wind and passing clouds.
Monday 5th. Strong northerly wind and fine weather. Sea moderate.
Tuesday 6th. Fine weather throughout the day and smooth sea.
Wednesday 7th. Fine weather throughout the day and smooth sea.
Friday 9th. Fine weather prevails. Smooth sea.
Saturday 10th. Moderate southerly wind accompanied by fine weather and smooth sea.
column11: Saturday 10th. One Submarine and a Destroyer put in here for the night.

column10: Tuesday 11th. Fine weather but rather hazy. Sea comparatively smooth.
Monday 12th. Fine weather throughout the day and smooth sea.
Tuesday 13th. Overcast. Variable winds, unsettled weather.

column12: Arrival numbers jump from 2009 to 2100. 2010-2099 not used

column10: Wednesday 14th. Fine weather throughout the day with smooth sea.
Thursday 15th. Fine weather and smooth sea.
column11: Thursday 15th. We have today taken measure to protect our Dock Gates by stretching Torpedoes Netting across from half ebb to half flood.

column12: Looks like clerk was confused but settled on final version of Vesta

column10: Friday 16th. Moderate SW wind with exceptional fine weather. Sea smooth.
column11: Friday 16th. At 5.30am the local Trawl Ben Rinnes arrived with 49 survivors of HMS Hawk out of a total of 600 Hands, having been torpedoed by a German Submarine 40 miles off Buchan Ness.

column10: Saturday 17th. Overcast and gloomy.
column11: Saturday 17th. The Norwegian Steamer Lizzy put into this port for Bunkers reports having passed 2 Mines in Lat 56.41N and Long. 2.4 E. 20 yards apart.

column10: Sunday 18th. Fine weather and smooth sea. No other remarks.
Monday 19th. Fine weather and smooth sea.
column11: Monday 19th. The Norwegian steamer was the first beached in Torry Harbour. George Noble was Pilot.

column10: Tuesday 20th. Moderate southerly wind and smooth sea. Sky cloudy.
Wednesday 21st. Stormy weather and squally.
Thursday 22nd. Fierce South East gale and high sea, towards night the weather moderating and sea going down.
Friday 23rd. Moderate SE gale and squally. Miserable weather, sea rough.
column12: Weather report for 23rd but no ship arrivals showing.

column10: Saturday 24th. Wind East to SEast, showery and overcast, sea going down.
column11: Saturday 24th. HMS Driad, which was recently ashore at Orkney, has been drydocked today. Also HMS Oak.

column10: Sunday 25th. Fresh East to South East wind and choppy sea. Day ends with wind backing to N.E.
Monday 26th. Variable winds accompanied by heavy rain. Sea rough.
Tuesday 27th. Fine weather throughout the day and smooth sea.
Wednesday 28th. Same weather continues. No other remarks.
Thursday 29th. First part wind varying from NE to SE with rain, latter a fresh south east gale and high sea.
column11: Thursday 29th. The Dunleith put back with the loss of 2 men and ship disabled. The Torry and North Pier Brigades were called out.

column10: Friday 30th. Gale from SE continues with heavy rain.
column11: Friday 30th. The cargo steamer Wakefield put into the bay @ 11.30am. No tide flag shown.

column10: Saturday 31st. Same weather continues. No tide flag. Heavy sea running the Bar.
Sunday 1st Nov. Fresh south east gale and high confused sea
column11: Sunday 1st Nov. No tide flag shown owing to Freshet and heavy sea.

column10: Monday 2nd. Wind moderating and sea going down.
column11: Monday 2nd. Shipping resumed. Took in Wakefield drawing 19 feet aft behaved alright. Heavy rain throughout.

column10: Tuesday 3rd. Heavy rain sea rising and wind increasing awful weather
Wednesday 4th. Weather improving sea going down
Thursday 5th. Strong SE wind and squally rough sea on the bar.
Friday 6th. Weather improving sea going down.
Saturday 7th. Wind westerly weather fine sea smooth.
Sunday 8th. Wind SW sea smooth thrightening rain.
Monday 9th. Wind south west fine and clear sea smooth.
Tuesday 10th. Fine weather and smooth sea. Strong westerly wind prevailing.
Wednesday 11th. Strong westerly gale throughout the day and squally sea rough at the offing.
column11: There was a very curious tide. The water never ebbed less than 17 1/2 feet and at 2 hours flood we had 19 ft and H.W. 20 hours

column10: Thursday 12th. Fresh northerly gale throughout the day and rain squalls. Sea rough at the offing.
Friday 13th. Moderate to fresh gale and showery. Wind hauling to northward.
Saturday 14th. Strong NNW wind with frequent snow squalls wind inclining to howl out and range making.
Sunday 15th. Strong north to nor east wind and confused sea. Occasional rain squalls.
Monday 16th. Fresh northerly wind but sky clearing. Sea going down. Squalls less frequent.
Tuesday 17th. Fine weather throughout the day, sea rough sky partially overcast. Weather improving with very high barometer.
Wednesday 18th. Fresh westerly wind and overcast. Sea moderate.
Thursday 19th. Strong northerly wind and overcast. Sea rough.
column11: Thursday 19th. 3 schooners are Commandeered by the Government for sinking purposes.

column10: Fridy 20th. Strong northerly wind overcast and hazy. Sea smooth.
Saturday 21st. Fine weather but overcast. Sea smooth. Lazy at sea.
column11: Saturday 21st. The schr Riga has taken aboard 100 tons stone and is all ready to scuttle at any time.

column10: Sunday 22nd. Variable winds but continuous rain. Sea rising.
column11: Sunday 22nd. Telephone message at 7.30PM to fit the Patrol Boat out with 2 Pilots. Admiralty Orders.

column10: Monday 23rd. Fine weather and smooth sea. Sky clear.
column11: Monday 23rd. No Patrol Boat. Ballasted the Holland Schooner and shifted her to Torry Harbour.

column10: Tuesday 24th. Fine weather throughout and smooth sea.
Wednesday 25th. First part fine but sky overcast. Latter heavy and strong gale from WSW.
column11: Wednesday 25th. At 10pm the Trawler C.F. Monarch ran on to the Pier the North Side also a weather shore all hands napping their Bill. The Bay is full of Trawlers Poaching. 30 in number.

column10: Thursday 26th. Fine weather throughout the day, wind increased towards the night.
column11: Thursday 26th. We floated the Monarch at 10.30pm and took her to Torry Beach.

column10: Friday 27th.Strong SW wind, heavy sea running at the offing. Weather heavy Gale sprang up towards night accompanied by heavy rain.
column11: Friday 27th. We salved the S/S Monarch at 10.30 last night. She now lies on No 2 Pontoon

column10: Saturday 28th. Fine weather throughout with strong winds from SW.
Sunday 29th. Fresh SW wind and showery. Sea smooth.
Monday 30th. Variable winds accompanied by heavy rain. Sea smooth.
Tuesday 1st December. Strong WSW Gale. Clear and dry. Heavy sea in the offing.
Wednesday 2nd. Strong Southerly Gale and rain, heavy sea running outside.
column11: Wednesday 2nd. I hear by Telephone that there is a Vessel ashore at Portlethen.

column10: Thursday 3rd. Strong Gale veering from S. to Westward.
column11: Thursday 3rd. At 6.15AM the drifter Craig Bo, which was moored at Tilbury Wharf, broke her moorings and was carried out to sea by wind and tide. Another drifter was despatched to pick her up, which they did off Belhelvie. Another 15 minutes and she would have been driven on the sands. The wind at the time being about Hurricane Force and a heavy southerly sea outside. She was towed back at 9.30. The Barometer standing at 28.40, very low.

column10: Friday 4th. First part moderate and clear, middle and latter heavy rain. Wind S.W. fresh Gale and threghtening. Sea rough.
column11: Friday 4th. The Cremona showed signs of distress, want of coal. We brought her into port at 5.P.M.

column10: Saturday 5th. Strong Gale of northerly wind and squally, sea rough.
Sunday. Moderate southerly wind & fine weather. Sea smooth, latter part stormy.
Monday 7th. Fresh NorWest wind & fine weather. It blew very hard first part of the day, the Barom standing at 28.40
Tuesday 8th. Fine weather and smooth sea.
column11: Tuesday 8th. 8 Pilots were employed in transporting the two German Luggers over to Torry.

column10: Wednesday 9th. Wind variable sea smooth sky overcast.
column11: Wednesday 9th. 6 Pilots employed hauling Hollands Sch[ooner]. Zuluw from one side of Dock to other.

column10: Thursday 10th. Fresh Nor East wind, sky overcast and threghtening rain, sea moderate.
Friday 11th. Fresh increasing gale from S.E. Sea rising rapidly. Overcast and showery.
Saturday 12th. Heavy weather accompanied by snow squalls. Sea high and confused and dangerous to navigate in.
Sunday 13th. Heavy storm from South East.
Monday 14th. Storm abating but sea still high and dangerous.
Tuesday 15th. Strong northerly gale
Wednesday 16th. Fine weather throughout the day, sea smooth.
column11: Wednesday 16th. I hear that there has been a German raid on the Coast. Several German warships Bombarding Scarboro, Whitby and the Hartlepool [remainder of entry runs off page, not captured on photograph]

column10: Thursday 17th. Moderate SW Gale unsettled weather.
column11: Thursday 17th. Of the Bombardment yesterday, there were 77 Killed and 300 wounded.

column12: St Ninian scored out and St Magnus written

column10: Friday 18th. Moderate Southerly gale and overcast. Very rainy looking, sea moderate.
Saturday 19th. Fine weather throughout the day and smooth sea. Very hard frost.
Sunday 20th. Fine weather and smooth sea. Hard frost continues.
Monday 21st. Weather continues same.
Tuesday 22nd. This is the shortest day. Weather very fine and seasonable with hard frost . The river is strewn with young ice.
Wednesday 23rd. Fine weather accompanied by hard frost. Sea smooth.
column12: No Arrivals listed for 23rd December but there is a weather report.

column10: Thursday 24th. Fine weather and smooth sea. Very hard frost.
Friday 25th. First part fine, latter showery. Sea smooth, wind Southerly.
column11: Friday 25th. Red Lights on to assist a destroyer to sea.

column10: Saturday 26th. First part strong gale ranging from S.E. to S.W. Latter fine.
Sunday 27th. First part strong, ranging from South East to [rest of entry not captured by photograph]
Monday 28th. Fine weather and smooth sea.
column11: Monday 28th. Leading lts. were put on to assist 2 destroyers into Harbour.

column10: Tuesday 29th. Fine weather wind westerly sea smooth.
column11: Tuesday 29th. Leading Lts on to assist destroyers out of Harbour.

column10: Wednesday 30th. First part fine, latter heavy rain, wind backing into S.E. and showery. Sea rising.
Thursday 31st. Heavy swell outside. Wind westerly. Fresh. No other remarks.
